<Layout title="Heritage — Trove Collections" description="Four generations of pilots in one family. Here's how that became a shop.">
  <article class="heritage">
    <p class="muted breadcrumb"><a href="/about">← About</a></p>

    <h1>Where this comes from</h1>

    <p>
      Before Trove Collections became a collection of recommendations, it was a
      family story. This page is where our philosophy comes from — why aviation
      appears throughout the site, and why every recommendation here is expected
      to earn its place.
    </p>

    <p>
      The short version: <em>"If you fly it, you should be able to fix it."</em>
      Grandpa Jim said that to my grandfather — and my grandfather took it
      literally. He's the one in the family who earned the airframe-and-powerplant
      license, the one who stripped and re-covered a Stearman with his own hands.
      The license stopped with him. The standard didn't. Four generations of
      pilots later, it's still how this family decides what to trust — and what
      gets to be on this site.
    </p>

    <hr />

    <p class="lede">
      My family has flown for almost a hundred years. That isn't an opening flourish — it's
      the literal headline. Lt. Col. James A. Philpott — my great-grandfather, the
      family calls him Grandpa Jim — first soloed an airplane on September 8, 1928.
      He was 16. The brand is timing toward his centennial: September 8, 2028.
    </p>

    <p>
      Four generations later, I'm 20, a Communications major at the University of
      Arizona, hoping for an Air Force commission after I graduate. In between him and me are
      almost a hundred years of cockpits, a TWA test-pilot job that turned into a 490th
      Bombardment Squadron command, a Continental seniority-list #1 retirement
      handed off mid-flight over the Pacific on a frequency called <em>fingers</em>,
      three sisters flying for major US airlines, a regional-jet pilot cousin who
      flies aerobatic biplanes on weekends, a 1982 TV commercial featuring an acne
      stick, and the teaching Grandpa Jim passed down to my grandfather: <em>if you
      fly it, you should be able to fix it.</em>
    </p>

    <p>
      This is the long version of why every item on the shop has been somewhere.
      We come from people who go places.
    </p>

    <figure class="hero-photo">
      <img src="/images/heritage/family-portrait-4-pilots.jpg" alt="Captain John Philpott with his three pilot daughters" />
      <figcaption>Captain John Philpott with his three pilot daughters (Generation 2 + Generation 3).</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <hr />

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <h2>Generation 1 — Lt. Col. James A. Philpott (Grandpa Jim)</h2>
    <p class="muted gen-meta">1928 → 1972 → forever</p>

    <figure>
      <img src="/images/heritage/grandpa-jim-beverly-b25.jpg" alt="Lt. Col. James A. Philpott and Beverly with the B-25 Flagship of the Skull and Wings, painted with war-bonds tour stops on the nose" />
      <figcaption>Grandpa Jim and Beverly with the <em>Flagship of the Skull &amp; Wings</em> —
      his command B-25, dressed up for a war-bonds tour. Look closely at the nose:
      those painted city names — Kansas City, Battle Creek, Atlanta, West Palm
      Beach — are tour stops, connected by a painted route line. Beverly came out
      to visit him at one of them. Someone, thankfully, had a camera. If this
      reminds you of the war-bond tours in <em>Captain America</em> — same idea,
      except real. And at one of the stops, the captain got a visit from his wife.</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      First solo: September 8, 1928, age 16, in a Velie Mono Coupe — a single-engine,
      two-seat, high-wing trainer. Verified through family records and the 2003
      History Channel documentary credits. That date is a real anchor — it's the
      reason Trove Collections is timing toward 2028 as its centennial year.
    </p>

    <p>
      The career that followed runs straight through the spine of the 20th century:
      Army Air Corps first; hired by TWA in 1940 originally as a <strong>test pilot</strong>;
      recalled to active duty after Pearl Harbor. His unit was flying P-40s and
      early P-51s when the word came down: they were becoming a bomber squadron.
      On October 20, 1942, Grandpa Jim took command — <strong>the first commander
      of the 490th Bombardment Squadron</strong>, the B-25 Mitchell unit the war
      would come to know as the Burma Bridge Busters. The Skull &amp; Wings
      squadron insignia, painted on the nose of a B-25 named <em>Flagship of the
      Skull &amp; Wings</em>, originated in his command.
    </p>

    <p>
      The 490th had some notable names pass through it, too — Arnold Spielberg,
      Steven Spielberg's father, served as Communications Chief with the Burma
      Bridge Busters.
    </p>

    <p>
      Late in the war he flew <strong>Foreign Aircraft Evaluation</strong> at Wright
      Field — Wright-Patterson AFB — flight-testing captured German and Japanese
      aircraft against US fighters to find the weaknesses. Two test pilots would
      dog-fight a captured Axis aircraft against one of ours, then swap.
      Declassified, well-documented, real.
    </p>

    <p>
      He retired from active duty as Lt. Col. and went back to TWA as a line
      pilot, eventually Captain. Stayed in the Air Force Reserve. Got checked out
      on the KC-135 at Edwards AFB before TWA had even taken delivery of the
      airplane. That's also where he became friends with <strong>Bob Hoover</strong>
      and <strong>Pancho Barnes</strong> — the Edwards/Mojave/Right-Stuff-era
      social orbit, in his case real and documented, not borrowed.
    </p>

    <p>
      Hollywood-side, he served as <strong>President of the Associated Motion
      Picture Pilots</strong> — the stunt-pilot guild Pancho Barnes founded in
      1932. He retired from TWA in September 1972. The fact that he was friends
      with Bob Hoover and went on to be neighbors with him in Palos Verdes Estates,
      keeping their aircraft at Torrance Airport, is not a story we made up to
      sound impressive. It's the kind of detail that explains the rest of the
      family.
    </p>

    <h3>The published legend</h3>

    <figure>
      <a href="https://www.airandspaceforces.com/article/1086philpott/" rel="noopener">
        <img src="/images/heritage/philpott-article-page.jpg" alt="A page from 'Philpott Has the Last Word' — Air Force Magazine, October 1986." />
      </a>
      <figcaption>From the family's copy of the October 1986 issue — tap to read it in the magazine's archive.</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      You don't have to take our word for any of this. In 1986 — fourteen years
      after Grandpa Jim retired — Maj. Gen. Dale O. Smith (Ret.) published a
      memoir about him in <em>Air Force Magazine</em> that opens: "There are
      major legends and minor legends, and then there was Philpott." It has
      stories we didn't put on this page: a young Flying Cadet who "fell" out of
      a B-10's open bomb bay mid-practice-run and parachuted down still holding
      his clipboard, and another general who, asked about him decades later,
      knew him only as the one who flew through a hangar in Denver. The General
      admits the memoir might be a little distorted — his words, and fair
      enough. Legends usually are. Read it in the magazine's archive:
      <a href="https://www.airandspaceforces.com/article/1086philpott/" rel="noopener">
      <em>Philpott Has the Last Word</em>, October 1986 →</a>
    </p>

    <figure>
      <a href="https://youtu.be/dg34z6exdFw?t=0" rel="noopener">
        <img src="https://i.ytimg.com/vi/dg34z6exdFw/hq3.jpg" alt="The 490th Bombardment Squadron posed with a B-25 — from the History Channel documentary Burma Bridge Busters." loading="lazy" />
      </a>
      <figcaption>The 490th on film: <em>Burma Bridge Busters</em> — tap to watch the History Channel documentary.</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      And he's not just in print. In 2003, the History Channel aired a
      documentary on the 490th — <em>Burma Bridge Busters</em>. Much of what
      you'll see in it came out of our attic: Grandpa Jim's films and
      photographs, passed down to my grandfather, who provided them to the
      producers. There's a thank-you to the Philpott Family in the credits —
      the same credits that helped us verify dates on this page. A copy lives
      on YouTube:
      <a href="https://youtu.be/dg34z6exdFw?t=0" rel="noopener">watch it here →</a>
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src="/images/heritage/p40-beverly.jpg" alt="The P-40 fighter named Beverly" />
      <figcaption>The P-40 fighter Grandpa Jim named <em>Beverly</em> after his wife.</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <h3>Beverly "Tutu" Philpott (née Brown)</h3>
    <p>
      My great-grandmother. Grandpa Jim's P-40 was named <em>Beverly</em> after
      her. The grandkids called her <em>Tutu</em> — Hawaiian for grandmother,
      probably picked up through Grandpa Jim's TWA Pacific routes. She belongs in
      this story because she's the reason the airplane had a name at all.
    </p>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <hr />
    <h2>Generation 2 — Captain John Philpott</h2>
    <p class="muted gen-meta">Aerial Advertising → Sierra Pacific Airways → Continental Airlines → retired #1</p>

    <figure>
      <img src="/images/heritage/grandpa-jim-john-stearman.jpg" alt="Grandpa Jim and Captain John Philpott with the family Stearman 923" />
      <figcaption>Grandpa Jim and Captain John Philpott with the family Stearman PT-17 — Generation 1 and Generation 2.</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      My grandfather. Career arc: <strong>Aerial Advertising</strong> with the
      family Hollywood business based out of Torrance Airport, flying the family
      Stearmans (more on those in a minute) → <strong>Sierra Pacific Airways</strong>
      as a regional pilot → <strong>Continental Airlines</strong>, hired October
      1972, <strong>retired #1 on the seniority list 42 years later.</strong>
    </p>

    <p>
      Retiring #1 on a major-airline seniority list is rarer than it sounds. It
      means he outlasted every single pilot hired before him over a four-decade
      career. Most senior captains retire <em>on</em> the seniority list. Very few
      retire <em>at the top of it.</em>
    </p>

    <p>
      Along the way: <strong>Line Check Airman</strong> — the FAA-approved
      designation that lets a senior captain conduct line checks on other
      captains in revenue operations. Airlines reserve LCAs for their most
      trusted commanders. He's also a <strong>licensed A&amp;P mechanic</strong>
      — Airframe and Powerplant — which is the FAA credential that authorizes a
      mechanic to maintain and sign off on aircraft. He has the mechanic license
      because Grandpa Jim required it. The rule, in Grandpa Jim's words: <em>"If
      you fly it, you should be able to fix it."</em>
    </p>

    <p>
      Over 42 years he flew six transport types: <strong>Boeing 727, 737, 757,
      767, 777, and Douglas DC-10.</strong> Propeller-era to glass-cockpit, in
      one career.
    </p>

    <h3>The Pacific frequency handoff — September 1972</h3>

    <p>
      The single best story in the whole heritage. The hand-off from Generation 1
      to Generation 2, captured in one September 1972 afternoon at LAX:
    </p>

    <p>
      Grandpa Jim's TWA retirement flight was Honolulu → LAX. Somewhere over the
      Pacific, his airplane crossed paths with a Continental pilot — a friend of
      his — flying the opposite direction, LAX → Honolulu. The Continental pilot
      had heard through the grapevine that John had been offered a position at
      Continental, and relayed the news to Grandpa Jim mid-flight on
      <em>fingers</em> — 123.45, the air-to-air frequency pilots use over oceanic
      airspace where there's no controller.
    </p>

    <p>
      Meanwhile, back at LAX, John was being summoned to Continental's Flight
      Operations Office. He met with <strong>Captain "Red" Stubben</strong>,
      Continental's Vice President of Flight Operations, who offered him a
      position on the Continental New Hire list. Stubben noticed John kept
      checking his watch. Asked if he had somewhere to be — knowing exactly where:
      Grandpa Jim's retirement flight was inbound.
    </p>

    <p class="quote">
      <em>"You got somewhere to be?"</em>
    </p>

    <p>
      Stubben tapped John on the back with the formal welcome, handed him a pass
      to ride the Continental bus over to the terminal, and sent him to meet
      Grandpa Jim's retirement landing at the gate. John's official hire date
      was October 1972. The same week the previous generation walked off the
      flight deck for the last time, the next generation walked on. With the news
      delivered, somewhere over the Pacific, on 123.45.
    </p>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <hr />
    <h2>The family Hollywood operation</h2>

    <figure>
      <img src="/images/heritage/aerial-advertising-stearmans.jpg" alt="The family Stearmans in the Hollywood aerial-advertising era" />
      <figcaption>The family Stearmans, Hollywood aerial-advertising era.</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Before the airline years, the Philpotts ran a Hollywood aerial-advertising
      business out of Torrance Airport. The fleet was Boeing Stearman PT-17
      biplanes, originally painted red with white sunburst stripes. The Stearmans
      worked banner-tow, sky-typing, and commercial-film aviation. They appeared
      in the Beach Boys <em>Endless Summer</em> poster artwork, a 1970s Hollywood
      aerial-advertising flyer, and most memorably a 1982 TV commercial for an
      acne product called <strong>Zit Stick</strong> — 33 seconds, archived on
      YouTube, in which the Stearman is staged to look as if it's shooting Zit
      Stick down at a beach in place of bullets. Captain John was the pilot in
      command for filming; a blonde model rides up front and is presented on
      camera as the pilot.
    </p>

    <p>
      Captain John personally stripped and re-covered the airframe of the family Stearman —
      strip to airframe, replace the fabric covering, re-dope, repaint,
      recertify. During that re-cover he repainted it from the original
      red-and-white to <strong>blue with silver sunburst stripes</strong>. That's
      the version my mom (Micki) is standing on the wing root of, below.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src="/images/heritage/micki-stearman-blue.jpg" alt="Micki standing at the cockpit of the family Boeing Stearman PT-17 in its blue-and-silver sunburst scheme, after Captain John's re-cover." />
      <figcaption>My mom on the family Stearman in the blue sunburst scheme — my grandfather's
      re-cover, fabric to paint, with his own hands. The paint looked even better
      in person.</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      The family no longer owns any Stearmans. The last one was sold (year
      pending — Mom's still asking Grandpa). What stays is the rule, and the
      proof that the rule was real.
    </p>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <hr />
    <h2>The one holding the camera</h2>
    <p class="muted gen-meta">Babs — wife, mother, grandmother, pilot, family archivist</p>

    <figure>
      <img src="/images/heritage/babs-hangar.jpg" alt="Babs at the hangar with her daughters Micki and Kristen — Kristen wearing rollerblades." width="1400" height="937" />
      <figcaption>Babs at the hangar with two of her three captains — my mom, and Auntie
      Kristen on rollerblades. For once, Babs is in front of the camera.</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Go back through the last fifty years of photographs on this page. The
      Stearmans at Torrance. The hangar at Camarillo. The retirement party.
      Three daughters growing up at airports. Now notice who's missing from
      almost all of them.
    </p>

    <p>
      That's my grandma — <strong>Barbara, but nobody has ever called her
      anything but Babs</strong>. For decades she has been standing exactly one
      camera-width outside this family's history, holding the thing that made
      the history keepable. Photographers are the one kind of archivist who pay
      for the archive by being absent from it. The modern half of everything on
      this page — so much of everything on this <em>site</em> — exists because
      Babs decided some ordinary Tuesday at the airport was worth saving. She
      was right every time.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src="/images/heritage/babs-mic-paris.jpg" alt="Micki and Babs together on a trip to Paris." width="1038" height="1600" />
      <figcaption>Babs on the road in Paris with my mom. Both of them in the frame,
      which means a stranger got handed the camera.</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      And don't mistake her for a spectator. She flies too — she soloed on
      January 14, 1976, at 24, in N3084S, and the family has the
      faded proof: a first-solo photo, hand on the tail, the same rite of
      passage as everyone else on this page. Married to a captain,
      mother of three captains, grandmother of a captain and an editorial
      director — and the reason any of us can prove any of it happened. In a
      family that measures itself in logbooks, hers might be the most complete
      one of all: it includes everybody.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src="/images/heritage/babs-first-solo-1976.jpg" alt="Babs's first-solo photo — January 14, 1976, hand on the tail of N3084S." width="1400" height="1050" />
      <figcaption>January 14, 1976 — Babs, 24, hand on the tail of N3084S after her
      first solo. Faded, creased, and kept for fifty years. Somebody else had to
      hold the camera for once.</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <figure>
      <img src="/images/heritage/babs-john.jpg" alt="Captain John and Babs, dressed up at sunset." width="1400" height="1404" />
      <figcaption>Babs and Captain John. Behind every long airline career is the
      person who held the family steady — and in this family, she also held the camera.</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      The family rule is &ldquo;if you fly it, you should be able to fix
      it.&rdquo; Babs has a quieter one: <em>if you love it, take the
      picture.</em> This whole site is us finally learning her rule.
    </p>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <hr />
    <h2>Generation 3 — Three sisters, three cockpits</h2>
    <p class="muted gen-meta">Three pilots at major US airlines</p>

    <figure>
      <img src="/images/heritage/micki-kristen-flying.jpg" alt="Micki and Auntie Kristen flying together" />
      <figcaption>My mom and Auntie Kristen, flying together back in their
      regional-airline days — early-morning coffees, getting their mojo going.</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <figure>
      <img src="/images/heritage/john-angie-t28.jpg" alt="Auntie Angie and Captain John beside the T-28 the family once flew, in Navy trainer colors" />
      <figcaption>Auntie Angie and my grandfather with the T-28 the family flew back then — Navy trainer colors and all.</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <figure>
      <img src="/images/heritage/micki-777-engine.jpg" alt="Micki in a white shirt and slacks beside an airliner engine many times her height." width="1085" height="1450" />
      <figcaption>My mom at the office.</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      My mom, <strong>Michelle ("Micki") Sharp</strong>. 30-year airline career
      — she started in cargo and at the regionals, where the flying is both
      domestic and international right off the bat, and now flies
      international at a major US airline. 40 years aloft since her first lesson. Soloed at 17. Once
      ferried a Harbin Y-12 from Kunming, China to Lusaka, Zambia. The kind of
      résumé that doesn't need adjectives.
    </p>

    <p>
      Her sister <strong>Auntie Kristen</strong> — Kristen Powell. Started at
      the regionals — domestic and international from the start — then came up
      through the B737, B757/B767, and B787, and currently flies the
      <strong>B777</strong> at a major US airline. Soloed at 17, same age as my mom. She's also the
      curator behind the Germany, Brazil, Argentina, Panama, and Sydney entries
      on this site — the antique mahjong set, the Ming Dynasty jade pendant, the
      polenta pan from Argentina, the German cuckoo clock, the D'Elidas hot sauce
      from Panama.
    </p>

    <p>
      Her sister <strong>Auntie Angie</strong> — Angela McGrath. Started at the
      regionals — domestic and international from the start — then the
      A319/A320 and 737, and currently flies the <strong>757/767</strong> at a
      major US airline (pilots call it the 756).
      Soloed on her 16th birthday in a Cessna 150, echoing Grandpa Jim's first
      solo at the same age in a Velie Mono Coupe. Two single-engine two-seat
      high-wing trainers, two pilots, one family, same milestone.
    </p>

    <p>
      That last sentence is the one we keep coming back to. It's why the family
      thread holds up.
    </p>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <hr />
    <h2>Generation 4 — Connor and me</h2>

    <div class="photo-pair">
      <figure>
        <img src="/images/heritage/connor-pitts-s1j.jpg" alt="Connor Philpott with his Pitts S1B" />
        <figcaption>My cousin Connor with his Pitts S1B.</figcaption>
      </figure>
      <figure>
        <img src="/images/heritage/eris-first-flight-lesson.jpg" alt="Eris on her first flight lesson, March 2022" />
        <figcaption>Me, on my first flight lesson — March 2022.</figcaption>
      </figure>
    </div>

    <p>
      My first cousin <strong>Connor Philpott</strong> — Auntie Kristen's son.
      Currently flying Canadair Regional Jets (the CRJ family) at a US Commuter.
      Weekend airplane is a Pitts S1B, a red aerobatic biplane with chevron-arrow
      stripes on the lower wings. Aerobatic flying is the family pastime; airline
      flying is the day job.
    </p>

    <p>
      And me. <strong>Eris.</strong> Got my student pilot certificate and FAA
      medical on my mom's birthday in March 2022, at 15. First flight lesson three
      days later. Turned 16 in May that year and became eligible to solo. I've
      paused active flight training while I'm in college and on track for an Air
      Force commission. I may go back to it later. The active-flying torch in
      Generation 4 right now is Connor's; I'm running the editorial side.
    </p>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <hr />
    <h2>The rule that explains all of this</h2>

    <p class="quote-big">
      <em>"If you fly it, you should be able to fix it."</em>
    </p>

    <p>
      Grandpa Jim said that to my grandfather. Grandpa lived it — A&amp;P license,
      hand re-covered the family Stearman. My mom heard it her whole childhood.
      I've heard it my whole life.
    </p>

    <p>
      It's the reason this is a shop where every item has been used. It's why we
      won't write up something none of us has actually carried. You don't
      recommend an airplane you've never flown. You don't recommend a travel bag
      you've never lived out of. <em>You should be able to fix it</em> applies to
      products the same way it applies to aircraft. We sell what we know.
    </p>

